{Introduction In this course, you will find a repertoire for Black against 1.d4 
based on the Nimzo-Indian. The repertoire against the Queen's Gambit is 
completed by our companion course, 'Short & Sweet: The Ragozin'. While this 
course is designed to get you up and running with the Nimzo-Indian in no time at 
all, if you would benefit from more in-depth analysis and coverage you might 
also enjoy our full course Lifetime Repertoires: The Nimzo-Ragozin 
https://www.chessable.com/lifetime-repertoires-the-nimzo-ragozin/course/17354/ 
These openings have been chosen with the purpose of providing a solid, reliable 
defence for Black which can last a lifetime. The Nimzo-Indian and Ragozin are 
top-class openings played at the very highest levels with success. The 
Nimzo-Indian is widely-regarded as one of the best defences against 1.d4 - in 
fact, this results in many players prefering Nf3 on move 3 to avoid it. In that 
case, we have you covered with our 'Short & Sweet: The Ragozin' course. You can 
try that out for free here: 
https://www.chessable.com/short-sweet-the-ragozin/course/27861/ All that's left 
is for us to wish you luck on your journey of learning and playing the 
Nimzo-Indian! Good luck and enjoy! Christof and Daniel} 1. -- *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Nimzo-Indian"]
[Site "S&S: The Nimzo-Indian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The Nimzo-Indian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-nimzo-indian/course/27858, variation/5080828"]

1. d4 {[%cal Be2e4][%csl Gd4,Ge4] Together with 1.e4, this is of course White's 
most direct and challenging attempt for an advantage.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4][%csl 
Ge4] Controlling e4 in the most flexible way possible.} 2. c4 {[%cal Gc4d5] 
White can't play e4 and get the 'perfect centre', so he settles for controlling 
the centre with the c-pawn instead.} e6 {[%cal Bd7d5,Bf8b4] A very flexible 
move. We prepare to wheel out our bishop to b4, pinning a knight on c3, or fight 
for the centre with ...d5.} 3. Nc3 {[%cal Be2e4,Gc3e4][%csl Ge4]} ({This is 
still the most popular move in this position, however at the top level} 3. Nf3 
{is being played for more often and it also scores better.}) {If you know your 
theory well, you should look forward to facing 3. Nc3 as White typically 
struggles to get even the slightest of edges after} Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1,Gf6e4][%csl 
Ge4,Rc3] This is the starting position of this course and a major branching 
point. The Nimzo-Indian was named after its pioneer in the early 20th century, 
Aron Nimzowitsch. Nimzowitsch advocated a new approach to openings, the 
hypermodern openings, which have the idea of controlling the centre with pieces 
instead of pawns. White has quite a number of major options here: • 4. Bg5 - 
We begin examining the Nimzo with the 4. Bg5 Leningrad variation and other rarer 
White tries. • 4. f3 is a sharp and topical try which can lead to very 
unorthodox positions. We will cover this, together with the closely-related 4. 
a3. • 4. e3 is White's most popular choice and one of the big Nimzo mainlines. 
• 4. Qc2 is White's second most common choice, with the point of trying to win 
the bishop pair without conceding doubled pawns. The Nimzo-Indian's biggest 
advantage is its flexibility. This means that Black can choose from 3-4 decent 
variations against each of White's major options. However, in order to have 
synergy with lines in the Ragozin, we have opted for variations where Black 
plays ...d5 early on. Depending on how White plays, we will often play ...0-0, 
...d5 and then either ...c5 at some point or ...b6 followed by ...Ba6.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Nimzo-Indian"]
