1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 ({4. e3, commonly known as the Rubinstein 
Variation, is, together with 4. Qc2, far and away White's most popular and 
challenging option against the Nimzo-Indian. It might seem strange to think that 
blocking White's dark bishop in like this is critical, but as we saw earlier, 
active development with} 4. Bg5 {can be met strongly by} 4... c5 {,}) ({and} 4. 
Nf3 {transposes to the Ragozin after} 4... d5 {.}) {4. e3 seems quite inflexible 
and committal, however it is important to keep in mind that White hasn't 
committed his g1-knight yet. This means that he has a couple of possible setups 
involving Ng1-e2, in addition to the more obvious Nf3 plans.} O-O {Black's most 
flexible option and probably the best. Black doesn't commit his central pawns 
too early, which allows us to opt for either a dark-squared strategy (with 
...c5) or a light-squared strategy (with ...d5), depending on how White 
continues. In most situations we will be opting for the light-squared strategy 
with ...d5, as this is in keeping with the Lifetime Repertoire course's theme, 
but in one specific case we go for a dark-squared plan: when White plays an 
early a3 to gain the bishop pair.} 5. a3 {[%csl Rb4] An idea we already 
encountered in the 4. a3 and 4. f3 lines.} Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6 $1 {[%cal 
Be6e5,Be5e4,Bb7b6,Bc6a5,Ga5c4,Bc8a6,Ga6c4][%csl Rc4]} ({We already saw this idea 
featured in *a previous line* after 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 O-O 6. f3 Nc6!. It is 
important for Black not to play the automatic} 6... d5 {instead, as White scores 
well and gets a slight edge after} 7. cxd5 {.}) {The point behind ...Nc6 is 
two-fold: it prepares the ...e5 break and possibly ...e4 later as well, and also 
it allows Black to target the c4 pawn in the typical way with ...Na5, ...b6 and 
...Ba6.} 7. Bd3 {White's main move, developing naturally.} e5 $1 {[%cal Be5e4] 
White doesn't have enough control over e4 which means that we can look to play 
...e4 ourselves.} 8. Ne2 {White's most common choice by far.} e4 $1 {[%csl Rd3] 
Grabbing space.} 9. Bb1 b6 {[%cal Bc8a6,Ga6c4][%csl Rc4] Preparing to attack 
c4.} 10. Ng3 {[%csl Re4] White counterattacks our e4 pawn instead of defending 
c4.} Ba6 {[%csl Rc4]} 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Bxc4 $15 {This position has been 
reached in one game so far and Black already has a slight edge.} 13. Bd3 {Now we 
can improve by playing as follows.} Na5 $17 {[%cal Ga5c4,Bc4d3][%csl Rc1,Gc4] 
with a dream good knight vs bad bishop position for us.} *

