[Comment "short-sweet-the-nimzo-indian/course/27858, variation/4740296"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 {4. Qc2, often known as the Classical 
Variation, is the most challenging and topical variation of the Nimzo-Indian, 
together with the Rubinstein Variation, 4. e3. White wants to get the best of 
the both worlds in this variation: the bishop pair, after a3 ...bxc3+, without 
incurring irritating doubled c-pawns after bxc3 Another important characteristic 
of 4. Qc2 is that White can now play 5. e4 without losing a pawn, if White 
chooses to. All is not doom and gloom for Black, however. The issue with 4. Qc2 
is that it does nothing to contribute to White's development. As a result, it is 
typical to reach positions in this variation where Black has a lead in 
development, while White has won the bishop pair. In this situation, Black needs 
to play actively in order to keep the initiative and not allow White's pair of 
bishops to wreak havoc.} O-O {Black's most popular choice. He remains flexible 
in the centre. Black does have two other good options though: 4... c5 and 4... 
d5.} 5. Nf3 ({White's most flexible choice. Our issue here is that the most 
natural move,} 5. Nf3 5... d5 {, allows White to transpose into a line which is 
outside our repertoire after} 6. cxd5 exd5 {.}) c5 {[%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]} 
({Black's main move here, exploiting the poorly supported d4 pawn. As mentioned 
before,} 5... d5 6. cxd5 {would take us out of our repertoire.}) 6. dxc5 
({Supporting the pawn with} 6. e3 {is completely innocuous. If White wanted to 
develop his kingside at the cost of locking in the bishop, he should play 4.e3 
and not place the queen on c2 in the first place. After} 6. e3 d5 {Black gets 
good play, trying to open the position against the queen on c2.}) Na6 $1 {[%cal 
Ba6c5,Gc5e4][%csl Ge4] We plan to regain the pawn with the knight - from c5, the 
knight can fight for the e4 square.} 7. g3 {Fianchettoing the light-squared 
bishop is White's most popular and probably best choice.} Nxc5 8. Bg2 Nce4 
{[%cal Ge4c3,Gb4c3][%csl Rc3] Aiming to double white's c-pawns.} 9. O-O Nxc3 10. 
bxc3 Be7 11. e4 d6 {[%cal Bf6d7,Gd7c5,Gd7e5][%csl Rc4,Rc3]} 12. e5 $1 {White 
needs to open the position for his bishops.} dxe5 13. Nxe5 Qc7 {[%cal 
Be7d6,Bf6d7,Bd7c5][%csl Re5]} 14. Qe2 Bd6 $11 {[%cal 
Bf6d7,Bf6e8,Bf7f6,Gc7e5][%csl Re5] This position has been reached nearly a 
hundred times. Over the next few moves, Black can look to kick away White's 
strong knight on e5 with ...Ne8 and ...f6 or ...Nd7.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Nimzo-Indian"]
[Site "S&S: The Nimzo-Indian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.Qc2 with 5.a3 Variation 1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The Nimzo-Indian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-nimzo-indian/course/27858, variation/4740297"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 {4. Qc2, often known as the Classical 
Variation, is the most challenging and topical variation of the Nimzo-Indian, 
together with the Rubinstein Variation, 4. e3. White wants to get the best of 
the both worlds in this variation: the bishop pair, after a3 ...bxc3+, without 
incurring irritating doubled c-pawns after bxc3 Another important characteristic 
of 4. Qc2 is that White can now play 5. e4 without losing a pawn, if White 
chooses to. All is not doom and gloom for Black, however. The issue with 4. Qc2 
is that it does nothing to contribute to White's development. As a result, it is 
typical to reach positions in this variation where Black has a lead in 
development, while White has won the bishop pair. In this situation, Black needs 
to play actively in order to keep the initiative and not allow White's pair of 
bishops to wreak havoc.} O-O {Black's most popular choice. He remains flexible 
in the centre. Black does have two other good options though: 4... c5 and 4... 
d5.} 5. a3 {[%csl Rb4] The main move by far. White collects the bishop pair, 
which is what he set out to achieve.} Bxc3+ {Of course, retreating isn't really 
an option - we have already lost too much time.} 6. Qxc3 {Taking with the pawn 
is completely pointless - there is no need to even analyse it, since play is 
similar to 4. a3. In this position, thanks to Black's flexibility, Black can 
choose from a wide range of setups: light square strategies start with 6... b6, 
while dark square strategies begin with 6... d6. However, true to our repertoire 
theme, we will be playing 6... d5.} d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gd5c4][%csl Rc4] This is 
only Black's 4th most common move, however it has become the near-exclusive 
choice of the chess elite in recent years - sometimes 6... b6 is also played. 
Black's idea is to stake out a claim in the centre and try to take advantage of 
our lead in development. Often, to do this we will be taking on c4, thus making 
white lose more time moving his queen.} 7. cxd5 $6 {White captures on d5, 
removing the tension, before we have a chance to take on c4. This is White's 4th 
most common move here, and it isn't very challenging. The issue here for White 
is that our bishop comes alive.} Ne4 {[%cal Ge4c3,Be6d5,Ge4g5][%csl Rc3] We can 
play in a number of other ways here, however this is the main move. Before 
recapturing on d5 with ...exd5, we throw in a little intermezzo so that White 
doesn't have the Bg5 pin available any more.} 8. Qc2 {The most natural option 
(and the best), but as we shall see, even on c2 the queen is not entirely safe.} 
exd5 {We are free to develop our light bishop actively now seeing as the 
diagonal has been opened.} 9. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7] Developing the bishop outside the 
pawn chain before playing e3.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4][%csl Rd4]} ({It seems a bit 
unusual to block our c-pawn like this, but keep in mind that we need to 
prioritise active play to keep our initiative. An interesting alternative here 
though is} 9... Bf5 {.}) 10. e3 Re8 {[%cal Gc6d4,Ge8e1][%csl Re1,Rd4] Setting up 
tactical ideas along the e-file based on ...Nxd4.} 11. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4]} g5 $1 
{[%csl Rf4] Keeping up the pressure on White.} 12. Bg3 g4 {[%csl Rf3] Again, 
forceful.} 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 c5 $15 {[%cal Ge8e5,Bc8f5,Bd8a5][%csl Rd4,Re5] 
Black retains his initiative with a good position. Possible ideas in the future 
are ...f6, ...Bf5 and ... Qa5+.} *

