pointless - there is no need to even analyse it, since play is similar to 4. a3. 
In this position, thanks to Black's flexibility, Black can choose from a wide 
range of setups: light square strategies start with 6... b6, while dark square 
strategies begin with 6... d6. However, true to our repertoire theme, we will be 
playing 6... d5.} d5 $1 {This is only Black's 4th most common move, however it 
has become the near-exclusive choice of the chess elite in recent years - 
sometimes 6... b6 is also played. Black's idea is to stake out a claim in the 
centre and try to take advantage of our lead in development. Often, to do this 
we will be taking on c4, thus making white lose more time moving his queen.} 7. 
Nf3 {Natural development.} dxc4 {[%cal Bb7b6,Bc8a6] We take on c4 to get White's 
queen to c4, so that we can later develop with tempo after ...b6 and ...Ba6.} 8. 
Qxc4 b6 {[%cal Bc8a6,Ga6f1] Preparing to play ...Ba6, developing with tempo.} 9. 
Bf4 {[%cal Gc4c7,Gf4c7][%csl Rc7] Targeting our c7-pawn.} Ba6 $1 {Sacrificing 
the c7-pawn. Typically in this variation, Black has more than enough 
compensation whenever White tries to greedily grab the c7 pawn.} 10. Qxc7 Qd5 
{[%cal Bf8c8][%csl Gd5,Rc7] Black needs to avoid the trade of queens to keep his 
initiative.} 11. Qc2 ({This is perhaps a better try for White than} 11. Qd6 $6 
{, which is also analyzed in the Lifetime Repertoires course.}) Rc8 {[%cal 
Gc8c1][%csl Rc2] Developing with tempo.} 12. Qb1 Qb3 {[%cal 
Bf6d5,Bc8c2,Gd5f4][%csl Rf4] Threatening ...Nd5 followed by ... Rc2.} 13. Nd2 
Qa4 $11 {[%cal Ga4d4][%csl Rd4] Attacking d4 with full equality.} *

